Docs.sourcestr7: This specification covers the minimum requirements necessary for design, selection of materials, construction, inspection, testing, and preparation for shipment.Centrifugal Fans shall be in accordance with API STD 673 Second Edition, January 2002.The purpose of this specification is to supplement or to amend the requirements of API STD 673. The requirements set out in this specification are identified in the same way as in API standard. Additional provisions that are not covered by API STD 673 are identified by extrapolation of the numbering scheme.Paragraphs of API STD 673 not mentioned in this document are fully applicable.

Where end-shield supported bearings are used, the inner seal shall be maintained at atmospheric pressure. Pressure {b}balancing{nb} from the cooling {b}fan{nb} shall be by use of copper or steel tubing, unless other materials are approved by the purchaser. Seals shall be designed to minimize the entry of fumes, dirt, and other foreign material into the stator enclosure.;71556,358;345977,358;Purchaser-approved fiber-reinforced materials may be used. The air intake opening shall be guarded by a grill or a metal screen fastened on the outside of the {b}fan{nb} cover. Requirements for grills or metal screens are covered in 4.4.10.5.;40356,235;222994,235;4.4.5.2.10 The design of the stressed parts of fans shall include fillets and proper evaluation of stress concentration factors (SCF) for the geometry to fulfill the combined operational requirements defined in 4.2. Areas of concern include the {b}fan{nb}, blade-to-disk intersections, keyways, and shaft section changes. For machines having fans with tip speeds in excess of 75 m/s (250 ft/s), all accessible areas of welds on fans shall be subjected to magnetic particle or liquid penetrant inspection (see 6.2.2.4 and 6.2.2.5).;52119,523;280193,569;Fans shall be constructed to minimize failure from corrosion or fatigue. When specified, the vendor shall demonstrate to the purchaser's satisfaction that the nonsparking qualities and durability required are provided by the {b}fan{nb} system.

NOTE:;79392,243;376827,398;Fans shall be directly mounted on the motor enclosure or may be on the inlet ducting in the case of TEPV motors. In all cases, the {b}fan{nb} motor assembly shall be designed for easy access and replacement. Fan assemblies shall meet the requirements of 4.4.10.6.1.;80077,258;379124,258;In cases where the 2nd or higher order lateral critical speeds may encroach on the running speed range separation margin, the test shall also be performed with the weights placed at the balance planes 180°out-of-phase. In cases where an overhung mass is present (e.g. a {b}fan{nb} or coupling) resulting in a bending mode with maximum deflections at the shaft end, the tests shall also be performed with unbalance weights placed on the coupling. The amount of unbalance to be added to the overhung mass shall be based on four times the allowable residual unbalance in the overhung mass (e.g. from API 671, the assembled coupling may be balanced to 40Wc/N, where Wc is the weight of the coupling and N is the maximum continuous speed ;133138,726;583410,727;During tendering phase, supplier shall provide the list of special tools related to the particular design of the proposed motor.

Any special tools necessary to dismantle the motor (such as, but not limited to, for rotor extraction, bearings, couplings, heat exchanger, cooling {b}fan{nb}...) shall be provided by Supplier.;14524,316;99423,438;In all cases, the fan motor assembly shall be designed for easy access and replacement. {b}Fan{nb} assemblies shall meet the requirements of 4.4.10.6.1. Where end-shield-supported bearings are used, the inner seal shall be maintained at atmospheric pressure. Pressure {b}balancing{nb} from the cooling {b}fan{nb} shall be by use of copper or steeltubing, unless other materials are approved by the purchaser. Seals shall be designed to minimize the entry of fumes, dirt, and other foreign material into the stator enclosure.;64949,357;332184,357;Fans shall be separately and individually balanced prior to mounting on the rotor shaft. {b}Fans{nb} shall be on non-corroding material or shall be effectively treated with a corrosion resistant coating (after {b}balancing{nb} of the rotor assembly).

 

   2.4.6.3.6 When specified, the residual unbalance of the rotor shall be determined in accordance with 2.4.6.3.4 and Annex F.;54895,367;297554,1302;Fans may be directly mounted on the motor enclosure or in the case of TEPV motors on the external ducting. In all cases the {b}fan{nb} motor assembly shall be designed for easy access and replacement. Fan assemblies shall meet the requirements of 2.4.10.6.1.;72491,251;358856,251;In cases where the 2nd or higher order lateral critical speeds may encroach on the running speed range separation margin, the test also shall be performed with the weights placed at the balance planes 180 degrees out-of-phase. In cases where an overhung mass is present, such as a {b}fan{nb} or coupling, resulting in a bending mode with maximum deflections at the shaft end, the tests also shall be performed with unbalance weight placed on the coupling. The amount of unbalance to be added to the overhung mass shall be based on four times the allowable residual unbalance in the overhung mass.;124238,589;578356,589;In all cases the fan motor assembly shall be designed for easy access and replacement. {b}Fan{nb} assemblies shall meet the requirements of 2.4.10.6.1.

Motors shall be in accordance with IEEE 841.;72598,190;358963,340;Balancing shall be conducted with half coupling.

Rotor shall be equipped with provisions, which allow addition of {b}balancing{nb} weights by use of bolts in specially threaded holes directly on the rotor body.

Balancing weights shall not be of lead or similar ductile material.;54516,273;296353,559;Balancing weights shall not be of lead or similar ductile material.

After {b}balancing{nb}, weights shall be tungsten inert gas (TIG) welded on the threads to avoid any removal.

Fans shall be separately and individually balanced prior to mounting on the rotor shaft.;54722,261;296845,797;NOTE: Annex F provides a method of determining the residual unbalance remaining in the completely assembled rotor and {b}balancing{nb} machine sensitivity check.

(Clarification;55264,170;299025,503;Manufacturing tests

Rotor {b}balancing{nb} check

Dimensional checks;106265,62;499988,624;Manufacturing tests consist of an unloaded overspeed test.

Rotor {b}balancing{nb} check shall be performed as per paragraph 2.4.6.3.4. Residual unbalance shall be mentioned in the test report.;106382,186;501396,425
